  <h1>Character Creation</h1>
  <p>
    Welcome to boot camp. In this section, you'll find a step-by-step guide to character creation in fifth edition Dungeons and Dragons.
    Everything you need to know, from point-buy to proficiecny bonus. We'll also be making an example character so you can get a feel for the
    workflow.
  </p>

  <h1 id="race">Race</h1>
  <p>
    Like in real life, everything in D&D always come back to race. Unlike in real life, you get to pick your race, and no one is definitively
    better than another. Except half-elves. They're crazy good in basically every edition of the game, for some reason.
  </p>
  <p>
    But the races available to you in Dungeons and Dragons are <em>way</em> more interesting than the boring ones you get in real life. You don't
    just roll the dice and get stuck as a Bolivian for 60 years. You get to be like an elf or an orc or a dragon person or something.
  </p>
  <p>
    You can find a list of playable races in the <em>Resources</em> menu. The ones listed on this site encompass only those which are present in
    my game. To account for every official race would be a herculean task, since the number has more than quintupled since 2014. (And in that
    time, only one new class!)
  </p>

    <h2 id="racial-traits">Racial Traits</h2>
    <p>
      There wouldn't be much point in having a bunch of different races if they were all the same. The things that make them different are what
      make them unique and interesting.
    </p>
    <p>
      That's where racial traits come in: a number of different stat bonuses and mechanical differences that distinguish the races from one
      another. Though each race has its own lineup of special traits, every one shares these five:
    </p>
    <ul class="trait-list">
      <li>
        <strong><em>Ability Score Increase.</em></strong> Most races provide a couple bonuses to your ability scores (more on those later), based
        on culture and physiology.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><em>Age.</em></strong> Functionally useless stat. Basically just for you to decide what age your character is at the beginning of
        the game.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><em>Size.</em></strong> Barely any applications in 5e, but you'll need to know it if you want to grapple a bigger creature. Small
        creatures can also move through larger creatures' spaces.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><em>Speed.</em></strong> This stat determines how far you can move in a single turn. It's normally related to size, but dwarves
        are an exception: with a Medium size and a Small speed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><em>Languages.</em></strong> This just tells you what languages you can speak. Most settings have a "Common" tongue, or something
        similarly boring in name.
      </li>
    </ul>

  <h1 id="ability-scores">Ability Scores</h1>
  <p>
    Okay, now pay attention, because this part is important. This is the part of the character sheet you'll be consulting every time you roll the
    dice for the entire game. Your <em>ability scores</em> are measures of your character's innate physical/mental capabilities, ranked on a scale
    from 1 to 20. There are six in total:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong><em>Strength.</em></strong> Raw physical power and athleticism. Used for hitting hard, climbing walls, and lifting heavy things.
      This stat is used in the calculation of most melee damage rolls.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong><em>Dexterity.</em></strong> Speed, reflexes, and agility. (Yes, I know Dexterity is fine motor function of the hands and fingers,
      but this game disagrees.) Used to keep your balance, dodge attacks, and aim ranged weapons.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong><em>Constitution.</em></strong> Resistance and fortitude. Used to not get sick, not get poisoned, and not breathe for a long time
      without dying. This stat has an effect on your total hit points. 
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong><em>Intelligence.</em></strong> Ironically, not intelligence. Instead of smart, this stat makes you well-studied. Used for
      remembering things and knowing things in general. Spellcasting ability for artificers and wizards.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong><em>Wisdom.</em></strong> Intuition, perceptiveness, and quick thinking. Used to survive in nature, spot hidden things, and detect
      lies. Spellcasting abiltiy for clerics, druids, and rangers.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong><em>Charisma.</em></strong> Likability, force of personality, and persuasiveness. Used to convince people, lie to people, and not
      get possessed by demons. Spellcasting ability for bards, paladins, sorcerers, and warlocks.
    </li>
  </ul>

