    <p>
      Okay, I may have fibbed a little right out the gate.
    </p>
    <p>
      You won't be consulting your ability scores every time you roll the dice. In fact, unless you want to know how long you can jump with a
      running start or know how much weight you can carry, you'll almost never consult them at all.
    </p>
    <p>
      So why are they even there?
    </p>
    <p>
      The truth is ability scores are just a relic of older editions. They're only still in the game because oldheads and traditionalists (me)
      would cry and scream if they were taken out. The <em>real</em> important numbers are your ability score <strong>modifiers</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The modifier for any ability score is equal to the score, divided by two (rounded down), minus five. Or, you can just use this
      nifty table I made up just for you.
    </p>

    <h2 id="ability-score-generation">Ability Score Generation</h2>
    <p>
      "But how does one know one's ability scores?" you may be asking. Well, there are actually a few different ways to figure out your stat
      lineup. All of them are viable options (well, most of them are), and each DM tends to favor one over the others.
    </p>
    <p><em>
      Remember: Add on your racial ability score changes <strong>after</strong> you've determined your scores with one of the below methods—not
      before!
    </em></p>

      <h3 id="4d6">The Classic</h3>
      <p>
        This method is also known as the 4d6 method, or the "4d6 drop one" method, for reasons which will become apparent in a second. Get your
        favored six-sided dice, and roll four of them. Take away the lowest roll, and add the remaining three. The sum is your score. Do this once
        for each ability score.
      </p>
      <p>
        This follows the sentiment of "get a number between 3 and 18" from back in first edition, but favors numbers at the upper end of that
        range to distinguish your character from the average person.
      </p>

      <h3 id="standard-array">The Standard</h3>
      <p>
        Do random numbers scare you? Do you prefer to keep away from gambling? Pussy. This is probably the method for you. Instead of rolling
        dice, you get an array of 15/14/13/12/10/8. Use each number exactly once, for whichever ability score you want.
      </p>
      <p>
        This one actually isn't that bad. You get some good scores, some average scores, and one pretty bad score. Instant character archetype!
      </p>

      <h3 id="point-buy">The Calculator</h3>
      <table class="table table-striped" style="float: right; margin-left: 16px; width: 150px;">
