      <p>
        The standard array is cool, but it sacrifices a lot of variety and customizability for the sake of simplicity. Excellent for new players
        or getting a quick start, but not so much for making unique and varied characters.
      </p>
      <p>
        If that sounds like what you're thinking, or you're an accountant by trade, this may just be the method for you: point buy. Instead of
        being handed your ability scores or rolling for them, you crunch some numbers to find out what they are.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each score has a point cost. A score of 8 is free, and you have to spend points to move up from there. So, two scores of 13 would cost 10
        points, one score of 15 and one score of 12 would cost 11 points.
      </p>
      <p>
        The goal of this fun little numbers game is to get an ability score array you're happy with, without spending more than 27 points. Funny
        enough, the standard array costs <em>exactly</em> 27 points.
      </p>

      <h3 id="3d6">The Fuck You</h3>
      <p>
        Taking off the kid gloves for this one. This method isn't too dissimilar from the classic, but with one key difference: the number of
        dice. No more 4d6 drop one. Fuck that. 3d6 drop nothing. Pure, unfiltered random chance from 3-18. This is how shit got done in first and
        second edition.
      </p>
      <p>
        What's that? You rolled four 3's? No you didn't actually—your DM rolled it for you. But at least you get to choose two good abilities,
        right? No you don't, actually. They're rolled in order. Fuck you.
      </p>

      <h3 id="colville">The Colville</h3>
      <p>
        To be completely transparent, this isn't officially sanctioned. It was created by Matthew Colville, a popular D&D YouTuber, and
        professional writer and game designer.
      </p>
      <p>
        Start with 4d6 drop one, <em>but</em> roll in order, starting with Strength. Once you've rolled and added your racial bonuses, give it the
        once-over. If you don't have at least two scores of 15 or higher, start over.
      </p>
      <p>
        The idea is to break new players' pre-conceived notions of their characters, which are often based on other characters or some weird
        edgelord fantasy. Or something intentionally obtuse like a guy who lights things on fire for no reason other than to be annoying.
      </p>
      <p>
        By making players <em>discover</em> their characters, you prevent the frustration of failing to create a character the game wasn't
        designed to accomodate, and you create a fun and useful exercise for practicing roleplaying skills.
      </p>

  <h1 id="class">Class</h1>
  <p>
    Now <em>this</em> is where things get good. Take a look at your character sheet. Just at random. Close your eyes, pick up the sheet, hold it
    in front of you, and then open your eyes again. Odds are you're looking at a stat determined by your class. That's how impactful a choice it
    is.
  </p>

