      <p>
      Have you ever played a video game? In that video game, was your character's general <em>aliveness</em> represented by a value labeled
      "health" or "vitality"? If so, say "Thank you, Gary Gygax."
    </p>
    <p>
      Dungeons and Dragons was the first ever game to use hit points to track aliveness. Before D&D, the closest thing we had was the number of
      men left alive in each unit in your favorite war game.
    </p>
    <p>
      Since video games run on computers, they use exponents and complex equations to determine hit points. But TSR thought it was better if you
      didn't need a calculator to play. So your retarded ass is in luck.
    </p>
    <p>
      The answer they settled on was rolling dice. It is a dice game, after all. Is the random element of hit point generation a little annoying?
      Sometimes, but it balances out the more you roll. Take a statistics class, dummy. And is it more simple than the equation Dark Souls uses
      for Vitality? <a href="https://eldenring.wiki.fextralife.com/file/Elden-Ring/vigor_health.png">Absolutely</a>.
    </p>

